        <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-6">Understanding Bubble Wrap Thickness & Protection</h2>
        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">10mm Bubble Wrap (Standard)</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Best for everyday glassware (drinking glasses, mugs, dinner plates). Provides adequate cushioning for normal handling and transport vibrations. Cost-effective for high-volume shipping. ≈ RM 0.10 per meter.</p>

        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">12–15mm Bubble Wrap (Premium)</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Recommended for delicate, high-value items (fine china, decorative ceramics, crystal). Better shock absorption, thicker air pockets provide more cushioning. ≈ RM 0.15–0.20 per meter.</p>

        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">20mm Bubble Wrap (Heavy-Duty)</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">For extremely fragile antiques, collectibles, or items prone to breaking. Overkill for standard glassware but ensures maximum protection. ≈ RM 0.25 per meter. Use sparingly due to cost.</p>

        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Anti-Static Bubble Wrap (Specialty)</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">For electronics and sensitive items. Regular bubble wrap builds static charge. Anti-static variant (RM 0.30+ per meter) prevents damage to electrical components.</p>
      </section>

      <section class="mb-12">
        <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-6">Best Packing Techniques for Glassware</h2>
        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Wrapping Individual Items</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">1. Wrap item 2–3 times in 10mm bubble wrap. 2. Ensure overlap so no gaps exist. 3. Tape seams gently (don't overtape — extra weight stresses bubble wrap). 4. For wine glasses: wrap stem extra protection (5–6 layers) as stems are most fragile.</p>

        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Layering in Cartons</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Place bubble wrap cushion (2–3 inches thick) at carton bottom. Arrange wrapped glassware. Add corrugated dividers between layers (see corrugated cardboard guide). Finish with 3-inch bubble wrap layer on top. Fill gaps with crinkle paper (not peanuts).</p>

        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Stacking for Safety</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Don't stack cartons with glassware more than 3 boxes high. Weight on lower boxes can crush items despite bubble wrap protection. Label boxes: FRAGILE, THIS SIDE UP.</p>

        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mb-4">Combining Bubble Wrap + Corrugated Dividers</h3>
        <p class="font-body text-on-surface leading-relaxed mb-6">Best practice: Bubble wrap around individual items + corrugated sheets between layers + honeycomb corner protectors. This triple-protection approach virtually eliminates breakage.</p>
      </section>

